What I Found in the Actual SCF 2022 Codebook
I pulled the official Federal Reserve codebook (codebk2022.txt), the official Federal Reserve bulletin.macro.txt macro file, and the SDA Berkeley combined extract documentation. Here's what's actually in the SCF — variable by variable — for fertility, household composition, and immigration analysis. Every claim below traces to a Federal Reserve source I read directly.
The X5712 Question — Definitively Settled
X5712 is capital gains income (variable name KGINC in the Federal Reserve summary file). The official bulletin.macro.txt defines the income variables explicitly:
WAGEINC = X5702
BUSSEFARMINC = X5704+X5714
INTDIVINC = X5706+X5708+X5710
KGINC = X5712              ← capital gains income
SSRETINC = X5722
TRANSFOTHINC = X5716+X5718+X5720+X5724
RENTINC = X5714
Your manual lookup was correct. The third-party document was wrong about this — and the same logic disposes of every other "fertility variable" claim it made:

"X5701 = ever had biological children" — false. X5701 is in the income variable range; it's not even on the list of demographic variables.
"X5710 = biological children living with respondent" — false. X5710 is interest/dividend income (a INTDIVINC component).
"X5711 = biological children not living with respondent" — false. Same range, also financial.
The whole "fertility module X5701–X5708" — does not exist. That entire range is income components.

The third-party document essentially fabricated a fertility module that the SCF has never had. It also misrepresented the X707 series (relationship codes are in the X8020/X102/X108–X226 sequence in the actual codebook, with codes 1=respondent, 2=spouse, 3=partner, 4=child, 5=grandchild, 6=parent, 36=foster child, etc., and the public file collapses several of these — code 12 → 5; 31, 32, 36 → 39; 9, 10 → 29). The roster does exist; the document just got the variable numbers wrong in some cases and made up entire sections in others.
What the SCF Actually Has for Household Composition
The household roster is real, and it's richer than what we used in Paper 2. Up to 12 people can be enumerated. For each person, the SCF captures:

Relationship to respondent (X8020, X102, X108–X226): biological/in-law child = 4, grandchild = 5, parent = 6, foster child = 36 (in internal data; collapsed into 39 in public). With this you can distinguish a respondent's biological/step children from grandchildren they're raising, from foster children, etc.
Sex of each person (X8021, X103, X109–X227)
Age (X14 reconciled age for respondent, X19 for spouse, X8022/X104/X110... for others)
Marital status of each member 18+ (X8023/X105/X111... — codes 1=married, 2=living with partner, 3=separated, 4=divorced, 5=widowed, 6=never married; public file collapses 3 and 5 into 4, and 2 into 1 except for the respondent and spouse positions)
Whether each person usually lives there (X8024/X106/X112...)
Whether each person is financially dependent on the PEU (X8098/X107/X113...)

There's also a derived KIDS variable in the Federal Reserve summary extract dataset, which the SDA Berkeley codebook describes as: includes natural children, step-children, and foster children of household reference person or spouse/partner — built from the household listing. It counts co-resident children only.
What the SCF Does Not Have for Fertility
This is the critical gap, and it's the same gap we identified before:

No "biological children ever born" question. There is no NSFG-style fertility module. The respondent is never asked how many biological children they have had — only what their household composition is right now.
No fertility intentions question. Nothing equivalent to NSFG's RWANT (do you want a/another child) or INTEND (do you intend to have a/another child).
No fecundity / impaired fertility question. Nothing equivalent to NSFG's FECUND (currently surgically sterile, non-surgically sterile, sub-fecund) or RSTRSTAT (sterilization status).
No help-seeking question. Nothing equivalent to NSFG's HLPPRG (have you ever sought medical help to get pregnant).
No voluntary-vs-involuntary childlessness item. The survey simply doesn't ask why someone has no children. The X5712 claim was wrong.

This means the SCF cannot construct an unplanned-childlessness outcome. The five signals we use in NSFG (RWANT, INTEND, HLPPRG, FECUND, RSTRSTAT) have no SCF equivalent — none. This is not a matter of better proxies; the survey simply does not collect this content. Childless respondents are observable in SCF (zero children in the household roster, never married/widowed/divorced/single, age past childbearing range), but the SCF can't tell you whether their childlessness is voluntary, involuntary, postponed, or ambiguous.
What the SCF Does Have for Immigration Analysis
The 2022 SCF added a substantial new immigration-related block — confirmed by the Federal Reserve announcement page and listed in the codebook's "Variables added since 2022" section:

X7404 — Respondent's national origin (ancestry/ethnic origin)
X7437–X7443 — Years lived in the United States (respondent and spouse)
X8049–X8054 — Spouse's race/ethnicity (mirrors what was already asked of respondents)
X8055–X8057 — Spouse's national origin
X6906, X7796, X6915–X6917 — Other new identity-related items (national origin follow-ups)

The race/ethnicity infrastructure has always been there:

X6809 — respondent's racial/ethnic identity (Hanna & Lindamood 2008 confirmed this; in the public file it's collapsed to 4 categories — White non-Hispanic, Black non-Hispanic, Hispanic, Other; in the internal file it's 5 categories with Asian split out from Other in 2022)
X6810 — secondary race
The Federal Reserve's bulletin.macro.txt builds derived variables racecl, racecl4, racecl5, racecl_ex from these, with 2022 splitting Asian out as its own category for the first time

This is genuinely useful for an immigration analysis. You could test things like:

Wealth and income gradients by years-in-US (using X7437–X7443)
Financial-balance-sheet differences by national origin (X7404)
Mixed-nativity household effects by combining respondent and spouse nativity/origin

But — and this is the crucial limitation for your thesis frame — there's no parental nativity variable. SCF doesn't ask whether the respondent's parents were born in the US, so you cannot construct a 1st/2nd/3rd-generation breakdown the way Paper 3 does in NSFG. You'd be limited to a 1st-vs-other split (foreign-born vs. US-born), with years-in-US as a continuous refinement for the foreign-born group.
What This Means for Your Thesis
Paper 4 (unplanned childlessness): NSFG framework is the only option. The SCF cannot support this analysis. The third-party document's claim of a direct voluntary/involuntary item was fabricated; the actual survey has no fertility intentions, fecundity, or help-seeking content at all. V1 stands.
Paper 1 (credit card debt) and Paper 2 (childlessness/parental status): SCF remains correct. Paper 2 in particular benefits from re-examining the household roster — you may be able to refine the parental-status proxy by distinguishing biological/step children from grandchildren and foster children (which the X8020 series allows). That's a legitimate V5 improvement to consider, though not a fundamental redesign.
A possible Paper 5 (financial life of immigrant-headed households): genuinely viable in SCF. This would lean on the new 2022 immigration variables — years-in-US, national origin, mixed-nativity couples — and test wealth/debt outcomes. It's a different paper from your current four, not a replacement for any of them. Whether you want to pursue it depends on how much methodological scope you have left.
Closing Note on Variable Verification
For future verification of any SCF variable claim, the two authoritative sources are:

The codebook itself: https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/files/codebk2022.txt
The Federal Reserve's official bulletin.macro.txt summary-variable program, which defines what each X-variable represents in the canonical Federal Reserve analysis: https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/files/bulletin.macro.txt

The Codebook Search tool at https://www.federalreserve.gov/apps/scfcb is the easiest interface for spot-checking individual variables. If a third-party document (or LLM output) makes a confident claim about an SCF variable that doesn't appear in those Federal Reserve sources, it's wrong.
